04614nam a22006255i 9780520352827DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19891989cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805203528277 a10.1525/97805203528272doi  a(DE-B1597)647678  a(OCoLC)1419790218  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aREL0170002bisacsh1 aKieckhefer/Bond, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSainthood :bIts Manifestations in World Religions /cKieckhefer/Bond; ed. by Richard Kieckhefer, George D. Bond. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[1989] 4cÂ©1989  a1 online resource (275 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- t1. Imitators of Christ: Sainthood in the Christian Tradition -- t2. Sainthood on the Periphery: The Case of Judaism -- t3. Prophet and Walt: Sainthood in Islam -- t4. Indian Developments: Sainthood in Hinduism -- t5. The Arahant: Sainthood in Theravada Buddhism -- t6. Sanctification on the Bodhisattva Path -- t7. The Sage as Saint: The Confucian Tradition -- tAfterword: Toward a Comparative Study of Sainthood -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEvery major religion exalts certain individuals who occupy a dual role. On the one hand they serve as exemplars of virtue to be imitated, and on the other hand they stand removed from other mortals, privileged and unique. Christianity knows them as saints, and in the study of religion the term has been taken over and applied to similar figures in other traditions. The essays in this volume analyze the role of the saint in Judaism, Christianity, Islam, Hinduism, Buddhism, and Confucianism, providing both a comparative and an interpretive view of sainthood.The notion of sainthood is problematic in two ways. First, can the category be usefully applied to individuals in religious traditions other than Christianity? How has it manifested itself, and what differences are there in the various manifestations of sainthood? Second, where individuals are considered to have risen above the norms in these different traditions, how is it possible to resolve the tension between the saint's imitability and his or her otherness, between imitating and venerating the saint? The authors consider these questions in relation to a wide range of individuals in all the major traditions.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aComparative Religion. 4aReligion. 7aRELIGION / Comparative Religion.2bisacsh1 aBond, George D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBond, George D., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCohn, Robert L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDenny, Frederick M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKieckhefer, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKieckhefer, Richard, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLopez, Donald S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTaylor, Rodney L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWhite, Charles S. J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052007189640uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052035282740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520352827423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520352827/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyt